"COMBAT SYSTEM"

The clashing of swords, the dueling reflexes; combat training is essential for
survival in the world of Ramas.  Combat takes place on a round-by-round basis;
each combatant gets a number of combat moves based on their dexterity,
encumbrance (hence also strength), and weapon.  Choice of weapons is dictated
by the style of combat and the nature of the foe.  Targets with little or no
armor may be felled with a well-placed dagger, whereas one will require a 
heavy weapon to deal with a well-armored foe.

An attack in combat is performed in the following sequence:

Whether by explicit command or by an automatic move from the &cWcombat profile&c0,
someone attacks their chosen foe.  They roll against their skill on three
six-sided dice; if they succeed, this means that the attack will indeed strike
the foe if not stopped.  

There are multiple layers of defense for the foe:

1)  Active Defense.  This involves dodging, blocking, parrying, etc.  The foe
may actively defend a set number of times per round, determined by their speed
and posture.  However, this defense may be exhausted by heated combat or even
neglected voluntarily - a skilled warrior  may block several sword thrusts, but
if greatly outnumbered, only their armor may save them.  If the active defense
fails, the attack strikes a specific location of the target's body, where armor
can offer further defense.

2)  Passive Defense.  This is the ability of armor to deflect  damage
harmlessly off its surface, without even absorbing the force of the blow.

3)  Damage Resistance.  This is the last line of defense, relying on the 
strength of armor or even the toughness of one's own body.  

Any damage that gets past these three defenses is dealt to the target.  Turns
are granted to each of the combatants, based on their agility and numerous
other factors.

See also:  COMBAT, COMBAT PROFILE, COMBAT POSTURE, DAMAGE.
