SKILLS

Skills are the rating of what your character knows and is capable of.  Next to
stats, they are the most important attribute of a character.  Both players and
computer-controlled characters gain skills over time.

To actually determine a character's success at a skill, three six-sided dice
are rolled.  The character must roll a number at or under their level of
proficiency, so higher numbers mean higher chances.

Because Tower of the Lost Order does not rely on levels or classes to actually
define the character's potential skills, skills are defined by their
relationships to other skills instead.  A skill has several important
attributes:  a base, a modifier, prerequisites, and defaults.  The definitions
of these terms follow:

&cWBase&c0:  Each skill rolls versus a character's statistic, or an average of
several statistics.  Most combat skills are determined by dexterity, although
the average of strength and dexterity is also common.  Most intellectual and
magic skills have intelligence as their base.  Other skills rely on wisdom,
constitution, or charisma, as appropriate.

&cWModifier&c0:  The modifier is added to the base, determining the actual
chance of success, and usually reflecting both the difficulty of the skill and
the character's proficiency at it.

&cWPrerequisites&c0:  Some skills require a certain level of mastery in other
skills or possibly a certain score in statistic before they can be learned and
used.  All prerequisites must be satisfied in order to use the skill.

&cWDefaults&c0:  Once the skill's prerequisites are satisfied, the skill may
be used.  Defaults represent related skills that may give some knowledge about
the skill being rolled; i.e. knowing how to fight with a broadsword gives the
player some idea of how to use a shortsword.  Defaults have an additional
modifier, usually reflecting how much the default skill aids the present
skill.  

A typical roll would go like this:

Jalastra has an intelligence score of 12, and wishes to search.  She has three
practice points invested in her search skill, which gives her a modifier of -1.
Hence, she must actually roll 11 or less on three six-sided dice to succeed.

The character does not need to invest any points in the skill in order to
take advantage of default rolls.  When the skill is rolled, the MUD picks
the best case out of the possible rolls.  If one has 30 points invested in
one's shortsword skill and only 2 in one's broadsword skill, the MUD will
use their shortsword skill as a default when using a broadsword rather than
the broadsword skill because of sheer aptitude, even after the -2 modifier
is applied to the shortsword roll.
